[5] Singapore: 38 cases, more than triple that of the same period last year
Date: Fri 22 Mar 2019
Source: Channel News Asia [abridged, edited]
https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/spike-measles-cases-in-first-11-weeks-of-2019-11366368


The number of measles cases in Singapore in the first 11 weeks of this year [2019] was more than triple that of the same period last year [2018], the Ministry of Health (MOH) said on Thu [21 Mar 2019]. As of 17 Mar 2019, there were 38 cases of measles recorded in Singapore, up from the 11 cases in the same period in 2018. There have been no deaths arising from the infection this year [2019], the MOH confirmed. This year's figure is the highest number recorded in the first 11-week period of the year since 2015.

MOH said there is currently no evidence of further spread of measles in the community, as majority of the reported cases this year were "single and sporadic local infections". It added that there were only 5 separate instances of the infection spreading to a family member or close friend.

Of the 38 people infected this year [2019], 25 contracted the virus locally, while the others were infected in the Philippines, Vietnam, Dubai and Thailand. Children made up 14 of the cases. Of these, 5 had missed their MMR (measles, mumps, rubella) vaccination and 9 were infants who were not due for their vaccinations.

Among the 24 adults, 15 were not known to have been vaccinated. The ministry said the majority of measles cases over the past 5 years were locally infected cases.

Measles vaccination is compulsory for all children residing in Singapore. As of 1 Feb 2019, a new requirement was introduced for foreign-born children applying for a long-term visit pass to Singapore to have their vaccinations. Those aged 12 and under will have to submit documentation of their vaccinations against diphtheria and measles.

In Ukraine, 11 people have died and more than 30 000 people have been infected this year [2019] in a major measles outbreak.

[Byline: Vanessa Lim]

