[8] Costa Rica: American family with 4 children suspected of having measles
Date: Thu 21 Mar 2019
Source: Q Costa Rica [abridged, edited]
https://protect2.fireeye.com/url?k=90529a22-cc6a3d40-90506317-000babd9f75c-7ace6354cd9c7815&u=https://qcostarica.com/american-family-with-four-children-suspected-of-having-measles/


The office of the Patronato Nacional de la Infancia (PANI) -- Costa Rica's child welfare service -- in Cobano, Puntarenas, says it will intervene in the case of the American couple with 4 children suspected of having measles The parents of these children, who have 5 other children, did not have them vaccinated and did not enroll them in any school in the Costa Rica.

The family of 11 is in strict isolation in Cabuya de Cobano, where they reside, to prevent them from infecting other people in their community. "We have already pronounced on our power to force the children to be vaccinated. In this case, what we ordered was that the local office initiate a special protection process, which means that the PANI will visit the family to assess if there are any violation of the rights of the children; in this case, health and education," said Vega.

It has become frequent for the PANI to intervene in situations like this. Last year [2018], Vega said, they were called by the Hospital Mexico due to the refusal of an Italian couple to vaccinate their newborn baby. The child was finally vaccinated with PANI intervention.

If the virus infection is confirmed, it would be the 1st autochthonous cases in Costa Rica since 2006, when the last patient was registered. These minors could have been infected with the virus by having contact with an American woman who visited them, who left the country on 12 Mar 2019 after presenting the characteristic symptoms of measles. Field research is also being done to locate potential contacts in the community where the family lives.

Health officials say these children have no relationship with the 1st imported cases that were registered in the country, of the 3 French citizens who arrived in Santa Teresa de Cobano on vacation in February 2019. The French family, who entered the country on 18 Feb and left on 6 Mar [2019], remained hospitalized for a week in the Puntarenas hospital. The epidemiological quarantine that the health teams made prevented spreading the highly contagious virus.

[Byline: Rico]

