[15] Madagascar
Date: Fri 22 Mar 2019
Source: IMAZPRESS [In French, trans. Corr.SB, abridged, edited]
https://protect2.fireeye.com/url?k=ca16a0c7-96309473-ca1459f2-000babd9fe9f-4fc853c9b7366b3a&u=http://www.ipreunion.com/actualites-reunion/reportage/2019/03/22/rougeole-a-madagascar-plus-de-mille-morts,99431.html


Between September 2018 and early March 2019, measles killed 1141 people, mostly children, according to figures from the Ministry of Public Health. Just under 100 000 cases have been recorded by the authorities and 104 of 114 districts are in the epidemic phase. Between malnutrition, refusal to seek treatment in a hospital and reluctance to vaccination, the big island struggles to fight against the disease.

The Anivorano-North health center welcomed 510 patients with "kitrotro" or "kisaosy", the 2 local names of the disease. Officially, only 4 have died. A number far below the reality, say many residents of the city, where the rumors are going well.

Just one year after a wave of plague that left more than 200 dead and rekindled terrors of another century, this is the island of the Indian Ocean facing another health crisis. "This is a major epidemic," says soberly Dr. Vincent Sodjinou, of the Malagasy antenna of WHO. "For almost a decade, vaccine coverage has not lived up to expectations and has increased the number of unprotected people over several generations." The country's current vaccination rate is only 57%.

"Normally, we only treat one case of measles every 2 months," says its leader, Dr. Ravohavy Setriny Mahatsangy, "since December [2018], we are already at 444". In the dock, he cites "social promiscuity, which facilitates the spread of the disease, the refusal to seek treatment in a hospital and reluctance to vaccination."

--
